data.content:
Your test works but `Assert.IsTrue` gives unhelpful failure messages (just "Expected: True, Actual: False"). MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions with clear diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));  // no built-in "all match" assert, IsTrue is fine here
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Your code | Better alternative | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Says "collection was empty" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Says "Expected count: 3, Actual: 5" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(admin)` | Says "Expected non-null" |

If you expect exactly one admin, `Assert.ContainsSingle` is even better — it returns the element and fails with a clear message if there are 0 or 2+:

```csharp
var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
Assert.AreEqual("Admin", admin.Role);
```
